The '''Golden Bull of 1222''' was a [[golden bull]], or [[edict]], issued by King [[Andrew II of Hungary]]. King Andrew II was forced by his nobles to accept the Golden Bull (Aranybulla), which was one of the first examples of constitutional limits being placed on the powers of a European monarch.<ref>Francis Fukuyama: What’s Wrong with Hungary?</ref>  The Golden Bull was issued at the year 1222 [[diet (assembly)|diet]] of [[Székesfehérvár|Fehérvár]].<ref>[http://www.rubicon.hu/magyar/oldalak/1222_aprilis_24_ii_andras_kiadja_az_aranybullat_fehervaron/ 1222. április 24. | II. András kiadja az Aranybullát Fehérváron - Rubicon Történelmi Magazin]</ref> The law established the rights of the [[Hungarian nobility]], including the right to disobey the King when he acted contrary to law (''jus resistendi''). The nobles and the church were freed from all taxes and could not be forced to go to war outside of Hungary and were not obligated to finance it. This was also a historically important document because it set down the principles of equality for all of the nation's nobility.<ref name="Kormos">Kormos, 2005</ref> Seven copies of the edict were created, one for each of the following institutions: to the [[Pope]], to the [[Knights Templar]], to the [[Knights Hospitaller]], to the [[Kings of Hungary|Hungarian king]] itself, to the [[Chapter (religion)|chapters]] of [[Esztergom]] and [[Kalocsa]] and to the [[Palatine (Kingdom of Hungary)|palatine]].

The charter's creation was influenced by the emergence of a nobility [[middle class]], unusual in the nation's [[feudal system]]. As a regular gesture of generosity, King Andrew often donated property to particularly faithful servants, who thereafter gained new economic and class power. With the nation's class system and economic state changing, King Andrew found himself coerced into decreeing the Golden Bull of 1222 to relax tensions between hereditary nobles and the budding middle class nobility.<ref>Molnar, 2001, pp. 32–33.</ref>

The Golden Bull is often compared to [[Magna Carta]]; the Bull was the first [[constitutional]] document of the nation of Hungary, while Magna Carta was the first constitutional [[charter]] of the nation of [[England]].<ref name="Kormos"/>

== Background ==

=== Grants of liberties ===

The Golden Bull that [[Andrew II of Hungary]] issued in the spring of 1222 is "one of a number of charters published in thirteenth-century Christendom that sought to constrain the royal power."{{sfn|Rady|2014|p=88}} [[Peter II of Aragon]] had already in 1205 planned to make concessions to his subjects.{{sfn|Holt|1992|p=25}} [[Simon de Montfort, 5th Earl of Leicester|Simon de Montfort]], supreme commander of the [[Albigensian Crusade]], issued the [[Statute of Pamiers]] in 1212, confirming the privileges of the clergymen and limiting the authority of the future rulers of [[County of Toulouse|Toulouse]] and [[County of Carcassonne|Carcassone]].{{sfn|Rady|2014|p=88}}{{sfn|Vincent|2012|p=62}} The statute influenced the [[Magna Carta]] of [[John, King of England]], which also secured the liberties of the Church and regulated feudal relationships in 1215.{{sfn|Vincent|2012|p=62}} The [[Holy Roman Emperor]], [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick II]], strengthened the authority of the [[Prince-bishop#Holy Roman Empire|imperial prelates]] in 1220.{{sfn|Holt|1992|p=25}}

Contacts between Hungary and these countries can be demonstrated during this period.{{sfn|Rady|2014|p=88}} Aragonese nobles settled in Hungary in the early 13th century.{{sfn|Rady|2014|p=88}} Hungarian participants of the [[Fifth Crusade]] could meet [[Robert Fitzwalter]] and other leaders of the movement which had achieved the issue of the Magna Carta.{{sfn|Ronay|1978|pp=77–80}} Two Hungarian prelates visited [[Canterbury]] in 1220.{{sfn|Rady|2014|p=88}} However, no direct connection between the texts of the Golden Bull and other early 13th-century grants of liberties can be demonstrated.{{sfn|Rady|2014|p=88}} Historian [[James Clarke Holt]] says, there is no need to assume that the authors of these documents borrowed from each other, because all these charters embodied the "natural reaction of feudal societies to monarchical importunity".{{sfn|Holt|1992|p=27}}

=== Hungarian society ===

{{Further|Kingdom of Hungary (1000–1301)}}

The existence of at least a dozen distinct social groups can be documented in Hungary in the 12th and 13th centuries.{{sfn|Molnár|2001|p=32}} Freemen and serfs were the two fundamental categories, but intermediate "semi-free" groups also existed.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=69}}{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=274}} Freemen could  in theory freely choose their lords, but they were in practice required to remain loyal to their masters.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=69}} On the other hand, unfree warriors could hold large estates which were legally protected against arbitrary actions of royal officials.{{sfn|Rady|2000|p=20}}

The highest-ranking royal officials were appointed from among men who regarded themselves{{sfn|Rady|2000|pp=23–24}} the descendants of either the Hungarian chieftains of the period of the establishment of the kingdom or of the foreign warriors who settled in Hungary during the subsequent centuries.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=69}} They were mentioned as "noblemen" from the end of the 12th century,{{sfn|Rady|2000|p=28}} but they did not form a hereditary elite.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=69}} The most prominent families started to name themselves after their forefathers in the 1200s, but their genealogies were often fabricated.{{sfn|Rady|2000|pp=23–24}} The ''[[Gesta Hungarorum]]'', which was completed around 1200, emphasized that the ancestors of many noblemen played a preeminent role in the [[Hungarian Conquest of the Carpathian Basin]].{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=185}}

Initially, each freeman was required to serve in the royal army.{{sfn|Rady|2000|p=20}} Those who were unable to perform this duty were obliged to pay taxes in the 12th century.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=275}} The majority of the [[castle warrior]]s were unfree, but freemen could also choose to serve the ''[[ispán]]s'' (or heads) of the royal castles.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=276}} They were to defend the royal castles and accompany the monarchs to their military campaigns in exchange for the parcels they held in royal lands around the castles.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=276}} Free castle warriors could also retain their own estates.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=276}} The highest ranking castle warriors started to refer to themselves as "freemen" or "warriors of the holy kings" to emphasize their privileged status.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=276}}

Thousands of foreigners{{mdash}}Slavs, Germans, Italians and Walloons{{mdash}}came to Hungary to populate the sparsely inhabited lands or to work in the centers of royal administration.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=276}} These "guests" preserved their personal freedom even if they settled in the estates of the aristocrats or churchmen.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=276}} [[Jews in Hungary|Jews]] could legally settle only in the centers of the bishoprics, but they actually also lived in other towns.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=255}} They were primarily merchants, engaged in long-distance trade.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=256}} [[Böszörmény|Muslims who settled in Hungary]] were primarily employed in the administration of royal revenues, but the presence of Muslim warriors is also documented.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=256}}

=== Transformation ===
[[File:Aranybulla1.jpg|thumb|250px|Golden Bull of 1222]]

[[Béla III of Hungary]], who ruled from 1172 to 1196, was one of the wealthiest European monarchs of his time, according to a summary of his revenues.{{sfn|Molnár|2001|p=46}} He earned income from the periodical exchange of coins, royal salt monopoly and customs duties, but significant part of his revenues came from the royal estates,{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=287}} because he owned more than half of landed property in the kingdom.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=70}} He decreed that each transaction proceeding in his presence was to be recorded, which gave rise to the development of the royal chancellery.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=70}}{{sfn|Rady|2000|p=66}} Thereafter private transactions were also frequently recorded and preserved at specific monasteries or cathedral chapters, known as "[[place of authentication|places of authentication]]".{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=70}}

Béla III's eldest son and successor, [[Emeric, King of Hungary|Emeric]], faced a series of rebellions initiated by his younger brother, Andrew.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=178}} Both the king and his brother, who seized Croatia and Dalmatia, made generous grants to their partisans to secure their loyalty.{{sfn|Makkai|1990|p=23}}{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=185}} Prelates and high-ranking officials supported Andrew against the king, but Emeric defeated his brother.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=17}} Andrew mounted the throne after the sudden death of Emeric's infant son, [[Ladislaus III of Hungary|Ladislaus III]], in 1205.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=75}}

Andrew appointed his former supporters to the highest offices, but most of his brother's former officials could retain their offices, because he needed their assistance.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|pp=17–18}} For instance, four of Andrew's first seven [[Palatine of Hungary|palatines]]{{mdash}}[[Csépán Győr]] and his brother, [[Pat Győr|Pat]], [[Julius I Kán|Julius Kán]] and [[Bánk Bár-Kalán]]{{mdash}}had held offices already during Emeric's reign.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=19}} The ''ispáns'' of [[Bács County|Bács]], [[Sopron County|Sopron]], [[Zala County (former)|Zala]] and other important [[County (Kingdom of Hungary)|counties]] were mostly nominated from among Emeric's former supporters.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|pp=18–19}} The heads of the royal household{{mdash}}including the [[Master of the horse (Kingdom of Hungary)|master of the horse]] and the [[master of the stewards]]{{mdash}}became the members of the royal council during Andrew's reign.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=19}} He always appointed one of his old partisans to these new offices.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=19}}

Andrew started to grant large areas of royal estates and significant sums of money to his former supporters.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=20}} For instance, Alexander of the [[Hont-Pázmány]] clan, who had helped Andrew to flee from his brother's prison, received 300 marks in 1217.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|pp=19–20}} Andrew's predecessors had also donated royal estates in perpetuity, but mostly those situated in the borderlands.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=427}} Breaking with this practise, Andrew gave away large domains which were located in the central regions.{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=427}} The new policy of donations, known as ''novae institutiones'' ("new arrangements"), significantly reduced the revenues of the ''ispáns'' of the counties, because one third of all royal revenues from their counties were due to them.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=20}} The "new arrangements" also diminished royal revenues.{{sfn|Makkai|1990|p=23}} Andrew introduced new taxes and ordered the exchange of coins twice a year to secure the funds to the maintenance of his royal court.{{sfn|Makkai|1990|pp=23–24}}{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=186}} He farmed out the collection of the taxes and the administration of the royal mint to Jews and Muslims.{{sfn|Makkai|1990|p=23}}{{sfn|Molnár|2001|p=33}}

According to a widespread scholarly theory, the appearance of wealthy landowners in the counties threatened the social position of both the free and unfree royal warriors.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=77}}{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=428}} Lesser landowners started to emphasize their direct link to the monarch.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=76}} According to the available sources, landowners from [[Hosszúhetény]] were the first to call themselves "freemen and [[Royal servant (Kingdom of Hungary)|royal servants]]" during a court case against the abbot of [[Pécsvárad Abbey]] in 1212.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=12}} Andrew started to grant the same status from the 1210s.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=12}} Royal servants were to serve in the royal army, but independently of the ''ispáns'' who were the commanders of the county troops.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=13}}

{{Quote|"Everyone knows that Hungary has seventy-two counties. The kings of Hungary granted these to meritorious persons and they could be revoked without offending those who held them. Their luxury, wealth and income, power, rank and security came from these counties. However, because of the profligacy of some of ... [some of the] predecessors [of Béla IV of Hungary], their rights over the counties had been diminished to a great extent, since [the kings] had granted in perpetuity properties, villages, and estates belonging to the counties to deserving and undeserving persons alike. Therefore, because of the diminution of the counties the ''ispáns'' had no men, and when they marched out, they were taken for simple knights."|''[[Carmen Miserabile|Master Roger's Epistle]]''<ref>''Master Roger's Epistle'' (ch. 10), p. 151.</ref>{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=14}}}}

Andrew's "new arrangements" stirred up discontent among his subjects.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=76}}{{sfn|Makkai|1990|p=24}} A group of dignitaries made attempts to dethrone him in favor of his cousins in 1209.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=22}} His wife, [[Gertrude of Merania]], who had persuaded him to make generous grants to her German relatives and courtiers, was assassinated in 1213.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=76}} He was forced to have his eight-year-old son, Béla, crowned king in 1214.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|pp=24–25}}{{sfn|Berend|Urbańczyk|Wiszewski|2013|p=425}} After he left for a crusade to the Holy Land in 1217, his deputy, [[John, Archbishop of Esztergom]], was expelled from Hungary.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|pp=22–23}} Andrew returned to Hungary in 1218.{{sfn|Makkai|1990|p=24}} Shortly thereafter, his chancellery issued a series of charters which were dated as if he had started to reign in the spring of 1204, thus ignoring the last months of his brother's reign and the entire period of his nephew's rule.{{sfn|Rady|2014|p=95}} According to historian Attila Zsoldos, Andrew wanted to invalidate the royal charters which were issued during the eighteen months before his actual ascension to the throne.{{sfn|Rady|2014|p=95}}

The royal council ordered the revision of the grants concerning the estates of the ''[[udvornici]]'' (or semi-free peasants) in 1220.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=24}} Next year, a similar decision was passed about the estates of the [[Castle folk (Kingdom of Hungary)|castle folk]].{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=24}} Andrew was forced to appoint Béla to administer the lands beyond the [[Drava River]] in 1220.{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=187}} The noblemen who had lost Andrew's favor assembled in his son's new court.{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=187}}

== 1222 movement ==

The circumstances of the promulgation of the Golden Bull are uncertain because of the lack of sources.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=2}} The Golden Bull itself is the principal source of the events which forced Andrew to issue it.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=2}} Royal charters and [[Pope Honorius III]]'s letters to Hungarian dignitaries provide further information about the political history of the year.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|p=2}}

On 4 July 1222, the pope urged the Hungarian prelates to apply ecclesiastical censures against those who had claimed that they did not owe loyalty to Andrew, but to Béla.{{sfn|Zsoldos|2011|pp=6–7}}

The available data suggest that discontented noblemen, many of whom had held high offices during Emeric's reign, staged a coup in the spring of 1222.{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=188}}

{{Quote|"In the kingdom of Hungary, it had been decided lately that the entire people should assemble twice a year, and our dear son in Christ, [Andreas], the illustrious king of the Hungarians is bound to appear in person among them. On such occasions the riotous crowd, liable to get confused and to lose its self-control, tends to make demands on the king that are not only unpleasant but may even be unjust, among others they may demand to divest of their offices and honours the magnates and nobles of the realm whom they hate, to expel them from the country and distribute their property among the people. These demands have confused the king, and in order to comply with the demands of the unruly crowd, he is offending against the principles of justice, and is violating peace, which will lead to the weakening of his royal power. He is afraid of refusing to comply with the unjust demands, as this might endanger his life and that of his family."|Pope Honorius III's Bull of 15 December 1222{{sfn|Érszegi|1999|p=191}}}}

== Main points of the Bull ==

=== Royal servants' rights ===

More than one third of the articles of the Golden Bull dealt with the grievances of the royal servants.{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=189}} The king promised that neither the ''collecta'' (an extraordinary tax) nor the [[freemen's pennies]] (an ordinary tax) would be collected on their estates.{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=189}} He also pledged that he would not force them to accommodate him and his officials.{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=189}} Royal servants who had no sons{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} were granted the right to freely dispose of their estates in their testaments.{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=189}} The Golden Bull limited the judicial power of the ''ispáns'', stating that  in the royal servants' estates they could administer justice only in cases concerning the tithe and coinage.{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=189}} Royal servants were exempted of the obligation of accompanying the monarch to military expeditions to foreign lands.{{sfn|Blazovich|1999|p=189}}

{{ordered list |list_style_type = upper-roman
| item1_value=2 | 1 = No nobleman may be arbitrarily arrested, nor can he be oppressed by the desire of any higher power.
| item2_value=3 | 2 = The Noblemen are declared to be exempt from the payment of taxes, nor will money be collected from their treasuries. Neither will their residences be occupied, nor their villages, and these may only be visited by those who have been invited. No taxes will be levied on the Church. 
| item3_value=4 | 3 = If any nobleman dies without a male heir, his daughter will receive a [[Daughters' quarter|quarter of his possessions]]; the remainder of his property shall be given to others, but if, as a result of their deaths, they cannot take possession of these properties, then these properties shall pass into the hands of their closest living relative; if this is not possible, then the King shall inherit them. 
| item4_value=7 | 4 = If the King wishes to send his armies outside of the Kingdom the Noblemen will not be under obligation to go with him, if the monarch doesn't pay them. However, if an invading army enters in the Kingdom, all of them must serve to expel it. 
| item5_value=9 | 5 = The Hungarian Palatine may judge everyone in the Kingdom without any differentiation; but he cannot take try any nobleman without the King's approval. 
| item6_value=11 | 6 = If foreigners arrive in the Kingdom, they must not receive honors and public positions without the Royal Council's approval. 
| item7_value=16 | 7 = No title or public charge can be inherited.{{clarify|date=August 2016}} 
| item8_value=24 | 8 = No Jew or Ismaelite can hold a public position (job). The Nobles of the Chamber, those working with monies, tax collectors and toll-keepers may only be Hungarian noblemen.
| item9_value=26 | 9 = Hungarian properties cannot be given to foreigners. 
| item10_value=30 | 10 = No-one, besides the Hungarian Palatine, the governors of Croatia and Slavonia, the King and the Queen Consort, can have more than one title or honor.
| item11_value=31 | 11 = In order for this document to be lawful, and implemented in the future, seven copies of it will be made, each sealed with the Golden Seal. The first will be sent to the Pope, the second to the Knights of Saint John, the third to the Templar Knights, the fourth to the King, the fifth to the archbishop of Esztergom, the sixth to the Archbishop of Kalocsa and the seventh to the Hungarian Palatine, so that these writings won't be falsified or confused.
